0 = a(n)*(16*a(n+1) - 2*a(n+2)) + a(n+1)*(-6*a(n+1) + a(n+2)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 17 2014
a(n-2) = n*binomial(2*n, n)/4 for n > 1. - _Eric W. Weisstein_, Nov 30 2017
D-finite with recurrence: (n+1)*a(n) +2*(-2*n-3)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 28 2020

A033877.name: Triangular array read by rows associated with Schroeder numbers: T(1,k) = 1; T(n,k) = 0 if k<n; T(n,k) = T(n,k-1) + T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k).
formula: As an upper right triangle: a(n, k) = a(n, k-1)+a(n-1, k-1)+a(n-1, k) if k >= n >= 0 and a(n, k)=0 otherwise.
Another version of A000007 DELTA [0, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, ...] = 1, 1, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1, 4, 6, 0, 1, 6, 16, 22, 0, 1, ..., where DELTA is Deléham's operator defined in A084938.

A033878.name: Triangular array associated with Schroeder numbers.

A033879.name: Deficiency of n, or 2n - (sum of divisors of n).
formula: a(n) = n - A001065(n). - _Omar E. Pol_, Dec 27 2013
G.f.: 2*x/(1 - x)^2 - Sum_{k>=1} k*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 24 2017
Sequence can be represented in arbitrarily many ways as a difference of the form (n - f(n)) - (g(n) - n), where f and g are any two sequences whose sum f(n)+g(n) = sigma(n). Here are few examples:

A033880.name: Abundance of n, or (sum of divisors of n) - 2n.
formula: a(n) = A001065(n) - n. - _Omar E. Pol_, Dec 27 2013

A033881.name: Abundancy of n-th abundant number: sigma(k) - 2k for k such that this is > 0.

A033882.name: Abundancy of the abundant or perfect numbers: m = sigma(n)-2n for n such that m >= 0.

A033883.name: Deficiency of the deficient or perfect numbers: m = 2n - sigma(n) for n such that m >= 0.

A033884.name: Deficiency of n-th deficient number: 2k - sigma(k) for k such that this is > 0.

A033885.name: a(n) = 3*n - sum of divisors of n.

A033886.name: Number of connected 4-regular simple graphs on n vertices with girth at least 4.

A033887.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(3*n+1).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n-k} C(n,j)*C(n-j,k)*F(n-j+1). - _Paul Barry_, May 19 2006
First differences of A001076. - Al Hakanson (hawkuu(AT)gmail.com), May 02 2009

Let p[1]=3, p[i]=4, (i>1), and A be a Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j] = p[j-i+1] (i <= j), A[i,j]=-1 (i = j+1), and A[i,j] = 0 otherwise. Then, for n >= 1, a(n) = det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A122070(n,k) = Sum_{k=0..n} A185384(n,k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 13 2012
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)*5^floor(k/2)*2^(n-k). - _Tony Foster III_, Sep 03 2017

A033888.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(4n).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} F(3n-k)*binomial(n, k). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 07 2004
a(n) = Lucas(2n) * Lucas(n) * Fibonacci(n). - _Ralf Stephan_, Sep 25 2004
a(n) = Fibonacci[(4*n + 2)] modulo Fibonacci[(4*n + 1)]. - _Artur Jasinski_, Nov 15 2011 (corrected by _Iain Fox_, Dec 18 2017)

A033889.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(4*n + 1).
formula: a(n) = 7*a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n >= 2. - _Floor van Lamoen_, Dec 10 2001
a(n) = A004187(n+1) - 2*A004187(n). (End); corrected by _Klaus Purath_, Jul 29 2020
a(n) = sqrt(1 + 2 * Fibonacci(2*n) * Fibonacci(2*n + 1) + 5 * (Fibonacci(2*n) * Fibonacci(2*n + 1))^2). - _Artur Jasinski_, Feb 06 2010

A033890.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(4*n+2).
formula: a(n) = S(n,7) + S(n-1,7) = S(2*n,sqrt(9) = 3), where S(n,x) = U(n,x/2) are Chebyshev's polynomials of the 2nd kind. Cf. A049310. S(n,7) = A004187(n+1), S(n,3) = A001906(n+1).
Let q(n, x) = Sum_{i=0..n} x^(n-i)*binomial(2*n-i, i); then a(n) = (-1)^n*q(n, -9). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 10 2002
Define f[x,s] = s*x + sqrt((s^2-1)*x^2+1); f[0,s]=0. a(n) = f[a(n-1),7/2] + f[a(n-2),7/2]. - Marcos Carreira, Dec 27 2006
a(n)=b such that (-1)^n*Integral_{0..Pi/2} (cos((2*n+1)*x))/(3/2-sin(x)) dx = c + b*log(3). - _Francesco Daddi_, Aug 01 2011

A033908.name: Least number of Sort-then-add persistence n.

A033909.name: Number of Sort then Add steps needed to reach a sorted number, or -1 if never reach sorted number.

A033910.name: Numbers n such that s(n)+s(n+1)+s(n+2)=t(n)+t(n+1)+t(n+2) where s(n)=sigma(n)-n, t(n)=|s(n)-n|.

A033915.name: Numbers n such that s(n)+s(n+1)+...+s(n+10) = t(n)+t(n+1)+...+t(n+10).

A033917.name: Coefficients of iterated exponential function defined by y(x) = x^y(x) for e^-e < x < e^(1/e), expanded about x=1.
formula: E.g.f.: -LambertW(-log(1+x))/log(1+x). a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling1(n, k)*(k+1)^(k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 12 2003
a(n) ~ n^(n-1) / ( exp(n -3/2 + exp(-1)/2) * (exp(exp(-1))-1)^(n-1/2) ). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 27 2012
E.g.f.: A(x) satisfies A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} x^n/n! * Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling1(n,k) * A(x)^k. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 09 2013

A033918.name: Triangular array in which n-th row consists of the numbers 1^1, 2^2, ... n^n.
formula: a(n) = A000312(m), where m= n-t(t+1)/2, t=floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2) or a(n)=(n-t(t+1)/2)^(n-t(t+1)/2), where t=floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). - _Boris Putievskiy_, Dec 14 2012

A033919.name: Odd k for which k+2^m is composite for all m < k.

A033920.name: Largest proper substring of n-th prime that is prime (0 if none).

A033921.name: Largest proper substring of 2^n that is a power of 2 (0 if none).

A033923.name: Base 3 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 22 = 211 in base 3, so a(22) = 2a(2)+1a(1)+1a(0).

A033924.name: Base 4 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 53 = 311 in base 4, so a(53) = 3a(2)+1a(1)+1a(0).

A033925.name: Base 5 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 104 = 404 in base 5, so a(104) = 4a(2)+0a(1)+4a(0).

A033926.name: Base 6 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 181 = 501 in base 6, so a(181) = 5a(2)+0a(1)+1a(0).

A033927.name: Base 7 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 287 = 560 in base 7, so a(287) = 5a(2)+6a(1)+0a(0).

A033928.name: Base 8 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 429 = 655 in base 8, so a(429) = 6a(2)+5a(1)+5a(0).

A033929.name: Base 9 digital convolution sequence.
formula: For example, 611 = 748 in base 9, so a(611) = 7a(2)+4a(1)+8a(0).

A033932.name: Least positive m such that n!+m is prime.

A033933.name: Least nonnegative m such that n!-m is prime.

A033935.name: Sum of squares of coefficients in full expansion of (z1+z2+...+zn)^n.
formula: a(n) is coefficient of x^n in expansion of n!^2*(1 + x/1!^2 + x^2/2!^2 + x^3/3!^2 + ... + x^n/n!^2)^n. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jun 09 2000
a(n) = n!^2 * [z^n] hypergeom([], [1], z)^n. - _Peter Luschny_, May 31 2017

A033936.name: a(n+1)=a(n) + sum of squares of digits of a(n).

A033937.name: Convolution of natural numbers n >= 1 with Fibonacci numbers F(k), k >= 3.

A033938.name: Palindromic primes n such that the period of 1/n is a palindrome.

A033941.name: Number of ways A002808(n) can be properly factored into 2 integers.

A033942.name: Positive integers with at least 3 prime factors (counted with multiplicity).
formula: Numbers of the form Product p_i^e_i with Sum e_i >= 3.
a(n) ~ n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 04 2013

A033943.name: Sum of coefficients of a polynomial associated to a family of digraphs.

A033944.name: Compare partial sums of A033881 and A033884; this is the sequence of common terms.

A033945.name: Record highs in A033885 (3n - sum of divisors of n).

A033946.name: Values of n corresponding to A033945.

A033947.name: Smallest primitive root (in absolute value) of n-th prime.

A033948.name: Numbers that have a primitive root (the multiplicative group modulo n is cyclic).

A033949.name: Positive integers that do not have a primitive root.
formula: Positive integers except 1, 2, 4 and numbers of the form p^i and 2p^i, where p is an odd prime and i >= 1.

A033950.name: Refactorable numbers: number of divisors of k divides k. Also known as tau numbers.

A033951.name: Write 1,2,... in clockwise spiral; sequence gives numbers on positive x axis.
formula: Equals A132774 * [1, 2, 3, ...]; = binomial transform of [1, 7, 8, 0, 0, 0, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Aug 28 2007

A033952.name: Write 1,2,... in a clockwise spiral on a square lattice, writing each digit at a separate lattice point, starting with 1 at the origin and 2 at x=0, y=-1; sequence gives the numbers on the positive x-axis.

A033953.name: Write 0,1,2,... in a clockwise spiral on a square lattice, writing each digit at a separate lattice point, starting with 0 at the origin and 1 at x=0, y=-1; sequence gives the numbers on the positive x-axis.
formula: a(n) = A033307(4*n^2 + 3*n - 1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Woods_, May 20 2012

A033954.name: Second 10-gonal (or decagonal) numbers: n*(4*n+3).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 8*n - 1 with a(0)=0. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Jul 20 2010
For n>0, Sum_{j=0..n} (a(n) + j)^4 + (4*A000217(n))^3 = Sum_{j=n+1..2n} (a(n) + j)^4; see also A045944. - _Charlie Marion_, Dec 08 2007, edited by _Michel Marcus_, Mar 14 2014

A033955.name: a(n) = sum of the remainders when the n-th prime is divided by primes up to the (n-1)-th prime.

A033958.name: In the '3x+1' problem, these values for the starting value set new records for number of steps to reach 1.
formula: Positions of records in A006667. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jul 22 2020

A033959.name: Record number of steps to reach 1 in '3x+1' problem, corresponding to starting values in A033958.

A033960.name: Convolution of natural numbers n >= 1 with Fibonacci numbers F(k), k >= 4.

A033961.name: Number of different sets ("cut sets") of triangles a regular (n+2)-gon can be dissected into; two triangulations of an (n+2)-gon are equal if all numbers of congruent triangles coincide.

A033984.name: Odd integers n such that 2^n == 16 (mod n).

A033985.name: Number of partitions of n into two or more distinct nonzero squares.
formula: G.f.: Product_{k>=1} (1+x^(k^2)) - Sum_{k>=1} x^(k^2). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jul 26 2020

A033986.name: Order of first letter of n-th month of the year.

A033987.name: Numbers that are divisible by at least 4 primes (counted with multiplicity).

A033988.name: Write 0,1,2,... in a clockwise spiral on a square lattice, writing each digit at a separate lattice point, starting with 0 at the origin and 1 at x=0, y=-1; sequence gives the numbers on the positive y-axis.
formula: a(n) = A033307(4*n^2 + n - 1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Woods_, May 18 2012

A033989.name: Write 0,1,2,... in a clockwise spiral on a square lattice, writing each digit at a separate lattice point, starting with 0 at the origin and 1 at x=0, y=-1; sequence gives the numbers on the negative x-axis.
formula: a(n) = A033307(4*n^2-n-1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Woods_, May 20 2012

A033990.name: Write 0,1,2,... in a clockwise spiral on a square lattice, writing each digit at a separate lattice point, starting with 0 at the origin and 1 at x=0, y=-1; sequence gives the numbers on the negative y-axis.
formula: a(n) = A033307(4*n^2-3*n-1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Woods_, May 20 2012

A033991.name: a(n) = n*(4*n-1).
formula: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - 3*a(n-2) + a(n-3) for n > 2. - _Harvey P. Dale_, Oct 10 2011
a(n) = Sum_{i=n..3n-1} i. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Dec 04 2016

A033992.name: Numbers that are divisible by exactly three different primes.
formula: a(n) ~ 2n log n / (log log n)^2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 28 2016

A033993.name: Numbers that are divisible by exactly four different primes.
formula: a(n) has exactly 4 distinct prime factors. omega(a(n)) = A001221(a(n)) = 4. - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Sep 21 2005

A033994.name: a(n) = n*(n+1)*(5*n+1)/6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} Sum_{j=1..n} i+min(i,j). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 15 2013

A033995.name: Number of bipartite graphs with n nodes.

A033996.name: 8 times triangular numbers: a(n) = 4*n*(n+1).
formula: For n > 0, a(n) = A058031(n+1) - A062938(n-1). - _Charlie Marion_, Apr 11 2013
a(n) - a(n-1) = A008590(n), n > 0. - _Altug Alkan_, Sep 26 2015
a(n) = A056220(n) + A056220(n+1). - _Bruce J. Nicholson_, May 29 2017
a(n)*a(n+k) + 4*k^2 = m^2 where m = (a(n) + a(n+k))/2 - 2*k^2; for k=1, m = 4*n^2 + 8*n + 2 = A060626(n). - _Ezhilarasu Velayutham_, May 22 2019

A033997.name: Numbers n such that sum of first n primes is a square.

A033998.name: Numbers n such that the sum of the primes <= n is a square.

A033999.name: a(n) = (-1)^n.
formula: Linear recurrence: a(0)=1, a(n)=-a(n-1) for n>0. - _Jaume Oliver Lafont_, Mar 20 2009
Sum_{k=0..n} a(k) = A059841(n). - _Jaume Oliver Lafont_, Nov 21 2009
Sum_{k>=0} a(k)/(k+1) = log(2). - _Jaume Oliver Lafont_, Mar 30 2010
Euler transform of length 2 sequence [ -1, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2011
Moebius transform is length 2 sequence [ -1, 2]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2011
a(n) = -b(n) where b(n) = multiplicative with b(2^e) = -1 if e>0, b(p^e) = 1 if p>2. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2011
a(n) = a(-n) = a(n + 2) = cos(n * Pi). a(n) = c_2(n) if n>1 where c_k(n) is Ramanujan's sum. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2011
a(n) = (1/2)*Product_{k=0..2*n-1} 2*cos((2*k+1)*Pi/(4*n)), n >= 1. See the product given in the Oct 21 2013 formula comment in A056594, and replace there n -> 2*n. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 23 2013
D.g.f.: (2^(1-s)-1)*zeta(s) = -eta(s) (the Dirichlet eta function). - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 27 2015
a(n) = T_n(-1), where T_n(x) are the Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} (-1)^k*A063007(n, k), n >= 0. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Sep 13 2016

A034000.name: One half of triple factorial numbers.
formula: D-finite with recurrence a(n) + (1-3*n)*a(n-1) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 03 2012
